{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 09:51:00.332004", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Submission accepted.\n\nSummary of submission:\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [server_access_router]\n- root_cause_name: [p4_table_entry_missing, flow_rule_shadowing]\n\nNotes:\n- Rationale: The diagnosis localized the missing/misapplied segmentation policy to the server-facing router (server_access_router). To enforce backend isolation the device should have access-control/forwarding rules (ACLs or P4 table entries) denying host → backend-web traffic; the absence or misplacement (shadowing) of such rules best matches p4_table_entry_missing and flow_rule_shadowing as root-cause types.\n- Recommended immediate remediation steps (not part of submission but actionable):\n  1. Verify and restore the intended ACLs/firewall policy on server_access_router to block traffic from user subnets (10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24) to backend subnet (10.200.0.3–.6), permitting only load_balancer (10.200.0.7) to reach the backends.\n  2. If using a P4/SDN data plane, check for missing table entries or priority/order issues that cause higher-priority allow rules to shadow the deny rule; install correct table entries with appropriate priorities.\n  3. Confirm load_balancer configuration (ensure it proxies and not exposes backends directly).\n  4. After applying policy, re-run reachability tests from hosts to backends to confirm block, and verify load balancer accessibility remains intact.\n\nIf you want, I can produce specific ACL or P4 table entry examples and the order/priority to apply on server_access_router.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 2371, "output_tokens": 349, "total_tokens": 2720, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 1664}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
